{"title_page": "1860", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1860|the Italian film|1860 (film)|other uses|Special:Search/intitle:1860}}\n{{Year nav|1860}}\n{{C19 year in topic}}{{Year article header|1860}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n* [[January 2]] &ndash; The discovery of a hypothetical planet [[Vulcan (hypothetical planet)|Vulcan]] is announced at a meeting of the [[French Academy of Sciences]] in Paris, France.\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; The [[Pemberton Mill]] in [[Lawrence, Massachusetts]] collapses, killing 146 workers. \n* [[January 13]] &ndash; [[Battle of T\u00e9touan]], [[Morocco]]: Spanish troops under General Leopoldo O'Donnell, 1st Duke of Tetuan defeat the Moroccan Army.\n* [[January 20]] &ndash; [[Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour]] is recalled as Prime Minister of [[Piedmont-Sardinia]]. \n* [[February 22]] &ndash; Shoe-making workers of [[Lynn, Massachusetts]], strike successfully for higher wages. The strike spreads throughout [[New England]], and eventually involves 20,000 workers. \n* [[February 26]] &ndash; White settlers [[1860 Wiyot massacre|massacre]] a band of [[Wiyot people|Wiyot Indians]] on [[Indian Island (Humboldt Bay)|Indian Island]], near [[Eureka, California]]. At least 60 women, children and elders are killed. [[Bret Harte]], newspaper reporter in [[Arcata]], reports the news to newspapers in [[San Francisco]].\n* [[February 28]] &ndash; The [[Artists Rifles]] is established, as the 38th Middlesex (Artists) Rifle Volunteer Corps, with headquarters at [[Burlington House]] in London.<ref name=Website>See http://www.artistsriflesassociation.org/regiment-artists-rifles.htm.</ref>\n* [[March 6]] &ndash; While campaigning for the [[1860 United States presidential election|presidency]], [[Abraham Lincoln]] makes a speech defending the [[right to strike]]. \n* [[March 9]] &ndash; The first [[Japanese Embassy to the United States (1860)|Japanese ambassadors to the United States]] arrive in [[San Francisco]].\n* [[March 17]] &ndash; The [[First Taranaki War]] begins at [[Waitara, New Zealand]], when [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] refuse to sell land to British settlers. \n* [[March 22]] &ndash; The [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany]] is annexed to the newly formed [[Kingdom of Italy]].\n* [[March 24]] &ndash; [[Sakuradamon Incident (1860)|Sakuradamon Incident]]: [[R\u014dnin]] [[samurai]] of the [[Mito Domain]] in Japan assassinate [[tair\u014d]] (Chief Minister) [[Ii Naosuke]] outside the Sakurada Gate of [[Edo Castle]], disaffected with his role in the opening of Japan to foreign powers.\n* [[March]]&ndash;August &ndash; [[Battle of Jiangnan (1860)|The second rout]] of the [[Jiangnan Daying]] destroys the [[Qing dynasty]]'s army of 180,000.\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; The [[Italian Parliament|first Italian Parliament]] meets at [[Turin]].\n* [[April 3]] &ndash; The [[Pony Express]] begins its first run from [[St. Joseph, Missouri]] to [[Sacramento, California]], with riders carrying [[Pony Express Bible|a small Bible]].\n* [[April 4]] &ndash; A new uprising erupts in [[Palermo]].\n* [[April 9]] &ndash; French typesetter [[\u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville]] sings the French folk song ''[[Au clair de la lune]]'' to his [[phonautograph]], producing the world's earliest known [[sound recording]] (however, it is not rediscovered until [[2008]]).\n* [[May 1]] &ndash; A Chondrite-type [[meteorite]] falls to earth in [[Muskingum County, Ohio|Muskingum County]], [[Ohio]], near the town of [[New Concord, Ohio|New Concord]].\n* [[May 6]] &ndash; [[Expedition of the Thousand]]: [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] and his troops depart from [[Genoa|Quarto]].\n* [[May 8]] &ndash; In [[Granadine Confederation|New Granada]] (modern-day [[Colombia]]) the southern state of [[Cauca Department|Cauca]] secedes from the central government, in protest at the suggestion of increase of presidential powers; [[Magdalena Department|Magdalena]] and [[Bol\u00edvar Department|Bol\u00edvar]] join it; [[Colombian Civil War (1860\u201362)|civil war]] erupts.\n* [[May 9]] &ndash; The U.S. [[Constitutional Union Party (United States)|Constitutional Union Party]] holds its convention, and nominates [[John Bell (Tennessee politician)|John Bell]] for [[President of the United States]].\n* [[May 15]] &ndash; [[Expedition of the Thousand]] &ndash; [[Battle of Calatafimi]]: Troops under [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] defeat the army of [[Naples]] in [[Sicily]].\n* [[May 17]] &ndash; The German association football club ''[[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]'' is founded.\n* [[May 18]] &ndash; [[Abraham Lincoln]] is selected as the U.S. presidential candidate for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], in Chicago, Illinois.\n* [[May 27]] &ndash; Garibaldi's forces take [[Palermo]], the capital of Sicily.\n* [[May 28]] &ndash; One of the worst storms ever experienced in the region hits the east coast of England, sinking more than 100 ships and killing at least 40 people.<ref>Among those rescued at sea is the crew of the [[brig]] ''Hannah'', captained by George Jezzard, the great-great-great-grandfather of actor [[David Suchet]].</ref>\n* {{OldStyleDate|12 June|1860|31 May}} &ndash; The [[State Bank of the Russian Empire]] is established.\n* [[June 30]] &ndash; A historic [[1860 Oxford evolution debate|debate about evolution]] is held, at the [[Oxford University Museum of Natural History|Oxford University Museum]].\n\n=== July&ndash;September ===\n* [[July 2]] &ndash; [[Vladivostok]] is founded in Russia.\n* [[July 9]] &ndash; The [[Florence Nightingale School of Nursing and Midwifery|Nightingale Training School and Home for Nurses]], the first [[nursing school]] based on the ideas of [[Florence Nightingale]], is opened at [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in London.\n* [[July 11]] &ndash; Mutsuhito (the future [[Emperor Meiji]]) becomes [[Crown Prince]] of Japan.\n* [[July 20]] &ndash; [[Battle of Milazzo (1860)|Battle of Milazzo]]: The forces of [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] defeat royal Neapolitan forces near Messina, bringing nearly all of Sicily under Garibaldi's control.[[File:Giuseppe Garibaldi 1870 Nadar.jpg|thumb|160px|right| [[July 20]]: [[Giuseppe Garibaldi|Garibaldi]].]]\n*[[August 13]] &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Pav\u00f3n]] (1791-1866) becomes unconstitutional interim [[President of Mexico]], replacing [[Miguel Miram\u00f3n]]. Two days later Miram\u00f3n becomes president again.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Pav\u00f3n|url=https://presidentes.mx/jose-ignacio-pavon|website=Presidentes.mx|language=Spanish|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[August 22]] &ndash; Assisted by the British Navy, the troops of [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] cross from Sicily to the Italian mainland.\n* [[September 1]] A solar [[coronal mass ejection]] hits [[Earth's magnetosphere]], and induces one of the largest geomagnetic storms on record.\n* [[September 3]]&ndash;[[September 5|5]] &ndash; The [[Karlsruhe Congress|First International Chemistry Congress]] is held in [[Karlsruhe]], [[Grand Duchy of Baden|Baden]].\n* [[September 7]]\n** The {{PS|Lady Elgin}} is accidentally rammed and sunk in [[Lake Michigan]]; hundreds drown.\n** [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]]'s forces capture Naples.\n* [[September 10]] &ndash; Piedmontese forces invade the [[Papal States]], hoping to link up with Garibaldi in Naples.\n* [[September 18]] &ndash; [[Battle of Castelfidardo]]: The Piedmontese decisively defeat the Papal forces, allowing them to continue their march into Neapolitan territory, and effectively reducing the [[Papal States]] to the territory around Rome.\n* [[September 24]] &ndash; [[Battle of Guayaquil]]: [[Ecuador]]ian forces, led by [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Flores]] and [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda Moreno]], take the port of Guayaquil from Supreme Chief Guillermo Franco, who is backed by [[Peru]]vian forces.\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n* [[October]] &ndash; [[John Hanning Speke]] and [[James Augustus Grant]] leave [[Zanzibar]], to search for the source of the [[Nile River]].\n* [[October 1]] &ndash; [[Battle of Volturnus (1860)|Battle of Volturnus]]: Garibaldi defeats the last organized army of the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]].\n* [[October 5]] &ndash; Austria, Britain, France, [[Prussia]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]] form a commission to investigate the [[1860 Druze\u2013Maronite conflict|causes of the massacres]] of [[Maronite Christians]], committed by [[Druze]]s in [[Lebanon]] earlier in the year.\n* [[October 17]] &ndash; [[The Open Championship]], also known as the British Open, is played for the first time at [[Prestwick Golf Club]] in [[Ayrshire]], Scotland. The event is won by [[Willie Park Sr]]\n* [[October 18]] &ndash; The first [[Convention of Peking]] formally ends the [[Second Opium War]].\n* [[October 18]]\u2013[[October 21|21]] &ndash; Beijing's [[Old Summer Palace]] is burned to the ground by orders of British general [[James Bruce, 8th Earl of Elgin|Lord Elgin]], in retaliation for mistreatment of several [[prisoners of war]], during the [[Second Opium War]].\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; A new [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] revolt begins in New Zealand.\n* [[October 26]]\n** Garibaldi again defeats the Neapolitan forces, advancing on [[siege of Gaeta (1860)|Gaeta]], the last remaining Neapolitan strong-point.\n** Meeting at [[Teano]]: [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] gives [[Naples]] to King [[Victor Emmanuel II of Italy|Victor Emmanuel II]], recognizing him as [[King of Italy]].\n* [[November 3]] &ndash; The combined forces of [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] and King [[Victor Emmanuel II of Italy|Victor Emmanuel II]] besiege King [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies]] in [[Gaeta]], his last remaining stronghold.\n* [[November 6]] &ndash; [[1860 United States presidential election|U.S. presidential election]]: [[Abraham Lincoln]] beats [[John C. Breckinridge]], [[Stephen A. Douglas]], and [[John Bell (Tennessee politician)|John Bell]], and is elected as the 16th President of the United States, the first [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to hold that office.\n* [[December 1]] &ndash; [[Charles Dickens]] publishes the first installment of ''[[Great Expectations]]'' in his magazine ''[[All the Year Round]]''.\n* [[December 7]] &ndash; After a fiercely contested campaign, [[Monier Monier-Williams]] [[Boden Professor of Sanskrit election, 1860|is elected]] as the new [[Boden Professor of Sanskrit]], at Oxford University.\n* [[December 20]] &ndash; [[South Carolina]] becomes the first state to secede from the United States.\n[[Image:Hms warrior.jpg|thumb|220px|right| [[December 29]]: {{HMS|Warrior|1860|6}} (restored).]]\n*[[December 24]] &ndash; Mexico's interim president Miguel Miram\u00f3n flees the country after being defeated in battle.<ref name=\"miramon\">{{cite web|title=Miguel Miram\u00f3n|url=https://presidentes.mx/miguel-miramon|website=Presidentes.mx|language=Spanish|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[December 26]] &ndash; First [[Rules derby]] is held between [[Sheffield F.C.]] and [[Hallam F.C.]], the oldest football fixture in the world.\n* [[December 29]] &ndash; The world's first ocean-going (all) iron-hulled and armoured [[battleship]], the (British) [[HMS Warrior (1860)|HMS ''Warrior'']], is launched.\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* Christians and [[Druze]]s clash in [[Damascus]], Syria.\n* In [[Buenos Aires]], leader [[Bartolom\u00e9 Mitre]] subverts the [[Argentine Confederation]], and begins to establish a new centralist government, with the help of [[Uruguay]]an [[Colorado Party (Uruguay)|Colorado party]] leader [[Venancio Flores]].\n* China agrees, in an [[unequal treaty]] imposed on it, to allow missionaries to proselytize throughout the country.\n* [[Discovery of the chemical elements]]: [[Robert Bunsen]] discovers [[caesium]] and [[rubidium]].\n* German chemist [[Albert Niemann (chemist)|Albert Niemann]] makes a detailed analysis of the [[coca]] leaf, isolating and purifying the [[alkaloid]], which he calls [[cocaine]].<ref>Niemann, Albert (1860). ''[[On a New Organic Base in the Coca Leaves]]'' (\"\u00dcber eine neue organische Base in den Cocabl\u00e4ttern\", published version of Ph.D. dissertation).</ref> \n* [[Napoleon III]], Emperor of the French, and [[Empress Eug\u00e9nie]] visit [[Algiers]] and stay at the [[Casbah of Algiers]].<ref name=\"WDL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8768/|title=Interior of Governors Palace, Algiers, Algeria|website=[[World Digital Library]]|year=1899|accessdate=2013-09-25}}</ref>\n* [[Augustana College (Illinois)|Augustana College]] is founded in Chicago, Illinois by Scandinavian immigrants.<ref>The college moves to [[Paxton, Illinois]], in [[1862]] and eventually splits into a Swedish college in Rock Island, Illinois, in [[1875]], and a Norwegian college in Sioux Falls, South Dakota, in [[1918]].</ref>\n* Britain produces 20% of the entire world's output of industrial goods.\n* The [[Russian Empire]] has c. {{convert|1250|mi|km}} of railroads.\n* The [[American South]] has c. 4&nbsp;million slaves.\n* 1860&ndash;[[1900]] &ndash; 14&nbsp;million immigrants come to the United States.\n* Approximate date &ndash; First recorded [[fish and chip shop]]s in the United Kingdom, Joseph Malin's in London<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2003/jan/19/foodanddrink.restaurants|title=Enduring Love|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|first=Jay|last=Rayner|authorlink=Jay Rayner|date=2003-01-19|accessdate=2019-09-30}}</ref> and John Lees' in [[Mossley]] near [[Oldham]], Lancashire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/10410058/Potted-histories-fish-and-chips.html|title=Potted histories: fish and chips|last=Hyslop|first=Leah|date=2013-10-30|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|accessdate=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n== Births ==\n=== January&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Takaaki Kato suit.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Takaaki Kato]]]]\n[[File:Charles Curtis-portrait.jpg|110px|thumb|[[Charles Curtis]]]]\n\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; [[Kato Takaaki]], 24th [[Prime Minister of Japan]] (d. [[1926]])\n* [[January 8]] &ndash; [[Emma Booth (The Salvation Army)|Emma Booth]], fourth child of [[William Booth|William]] and [[Catherine Booth]] (d. [[1903]])\n* [[January 17]]\n** [[Charles K. French]], American actor, film director, and screenwriter (d. [[1952]])\n** [[Douglas Hyde]], 1st President of Ireland (d. [[1949]])\n* [[January 21]] &ndash; [[Karl Staaff]], Swedish lawyer, politician, 11th Prime Minister of Sweden (d. [[1915]])\n* [[January 25]] &ndash; [[Charles Curtis]], [[List of Vice Presidents of the United States|31st]] [[Vice President of the United States]] (d. [[1936]])\n* [[January 28]] &ndash; [[W. G. Read Mullan]], American Jesuit, academic (d. [[1910]])\n* [[January 29]]\n** [[William Jacob Baer]], American painter (d. [[1941]])\n** [[Anton Chekhov]], Russian writer (d. [[1904]])\n* [[February 11]] &ndash; [[Rachilde]], French author (d. [[1953]])\n* [[February 14]] &ndash; [[Eugen Schiffer]], German politician (d. [[1954]])\n* [[February 18]] &ndash; [[Anders Zorn]], Swedish artist (d. [[1920]]) \n* [[February 25]] &ndash; [[Sir William Ashley]], English economic historian (d. [[1927]])\n* [[February 28]] &ndash; [[Carl Georg Barth]], American [[mathematician]], [[mechanical engineer]] (d. [[1939]])\n* [[February 29]] &ndash; [[Herman Hollerith]], American businessman, inventor (d. [[1929]])\n* [[March 2]] &ndash; [[Susanna M. Salter]], first woman mayor in the United States (d. [[1961]])\n* [[March 5]] &ndash; [[Sam Thompson]], American baseball player (d. [[1922]])\n* [[March 13]] &ndash; [[Hugo Wolf]], Austrian composer (d. [[1903]])\n* [[March 19]] &ndash; [[William Jennings Bryan]], American politician (d. [[1925]])\n* [[March 27]] &ndash; [[Frank Frost Abbott]], American classical scholar (d. [[1924]])\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[Sergey Reformatsky]], Russian chemist (d. [[1934]])\n* [[April 7]] &ndash; [[Will Keith Kellogg]], American industrialist, founder of the [[Kellogg Company]] (d. [[1951]])\n* [[May 2]] &ndash; [[Theodor Herzl]], Austrian founder of modern political Zionism (d. [[1904]])\n* [[May 7]] &ndash; [[Tom Norman]], English freak [[showman]] (d. [[1930]])\n* [[May 9]] &ndash; [[J. M. Barrie]], Scottish author (d. [[1937]])\n* [[May 15]] &ndash; [[Ellen Axson Wilson]], [[First Lady of the United States]] (d. [[1914]])\n* [[May 20]] &ndash; [[Eduard Buchner]], German chemist, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1917]])\n* [[May 21]] &ndash; [[Willem Einthoven]], Dutch inventor, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] (d. [[1927]])\n* [[May 25]] &ndash; [[James McKeen Cattell]], American psychologist (d. [[1944]])\n* [[May 27]] &ndash; [[Manuel Teixeira Gomes]], 7th President of Portugal (d. [[1941]])\n* [[May 29]] &ndash; [[Isaac Alb\u00e9niz]], Spanish composer (d. [[1909]])\n* [[June 13]] &ndash; [[Lancelot Speed]], British illustrator, silent film director (d. [[1931]])\n* [[June 20]] &ndash; [[Jack Worrall]], Australian cricketer, footballer, and coach (d. [[1937]])\n* [[June 22]] &ndash; [[Tom O'Brien (second baseman)|Tom O'Brien]], American 19th century baseball player (d. [[1921]])\n* [[June 23]] &ndash; [[Albert Giraud]], Belgian poet (d. [[1929]])\n* [[June 25]] &ndash; [[Gustave Charpentier]], French composer (d. [[1956]])\n\n=== July&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Lizzie borden.jpg|110px|thumb|right|[[Lizzie Borden]]]]\n[[File:Annie Oakley by Baker's Art Gallery c1880s-crop.jpg|110px|thumb|[[Annie Oakley]]]]\n[[File:Joseph Cook - Crown Studios 03.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Joseph Cook]]]]\n[[File:Georgina Fraser Newhall (1895).png|thumb|110px|[[Georgina Fraser Newhall]]]]\n* [[July 3]] &ndash; [[Charlotte Perkins Gilman]], American feminist (d. [[1935]])\n* [[July 7]] &ndash; [[Gustav Mahler]], Austrian composer (d. [[1911]])\n* [[July 16]] &ndash; [[Otto Jespersen]], Danish linguist, creator of [[Ido (language)|Ido]] and [[Novial]] languages (d.[[1943]])\n* [[July 19]] &ndash; [[Lizzie Borden]], American murder suspect (d. [[1927]])\n* [[July 31]] &ndash; [[Sir George Warrender, 7th Baronet]], British admiral (d. [[1917]])\n* [[August 3]] &ndash; [[William Kennedy Dickson]], Scottish inventor, cinema pioneer, and film director (d. [[1935]])\n* [[August 5]] &ndash; [[Louis Wain]], English artist (d. [[1939]])\n* [[August 7]] &ndash; [[Alan Leo]], British astrologer (d. [[1917]])\n* [[August 8]] &ndash; [[Eliza Putnam Heaton]], American journalist and editor (d. [[1919]])\n* [[August 9]] &ndash; [[Maude Gillette Phillips]], American author and educator (d. unknown)\n* [[August 10]] &ndash; [[Vishnu Narayan Bhatkhande]], Indian musician (d. [[1936]])\n* [[August 13]] &ndash; [[Annie Oakley]], American Wild West show performer (d. [[1926]])\n* [[August 15]]\n**[[Henrietta Vinton Davis]], American elocutionist, dramatist, and impersonator (d. [[1941]])\n**[[Florence Harding]], [[First Lady of the United States]] (d. [[1924]])\n* [[August 16]] &ndash; [[Jules Laforgue]], French poet (d. [[1887]])\n* [[August 20]] &ndash; [[Raymond Poincar\u00e9]], French president (d. [[1934]])\n* [[August 22]] &ndash; [[Alfred Ploetz]], German physician, biologist, and eugenicist (d. [[1940]]) \n* [[August 25]] &ndash; [[George Fawcett]], American actor (d. [[1939]])\n* [[August 26]] &ndash; [[Eudora Stone Bumstead]], American poet and hymnwriter (d. [[1892]])\n* [[September 1]] &ndash; [[Mary E. C. Bancker]], American author (unknown year of death)\n* [[September 2]] &ndash; [[Georgina Fraser Newhall]], Canadian author and the bardess of the Clan Fraser Society of Canada (d. [[1932]])\n* [[September 5]] &ndash; [[Andrew Volstead]], American politician (d. [[1947]])\n* [[September 6]] &ndash; [[Jane Addams]], American social worker, recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1935]])\n* [[September 7]] &ndash; Anna Mary Robertson Moses (aka [[Grandma Moses]]), American painter, centenarian (d. [[1961]])\n* [[September 13]] &ndash; [[John J. Pershing]], American general (d. [[1948]])\n* [[September 15]] &ndash; [[Mokshagundam Visvesvarayya]], Indian engineer, statesman (d. [[1962]])\n* [[October 23]] &ndash; [[Molly Elliot Seawell]], American historian (d. [[1916]])\n* [[October 31]] &ndash; [[Juliette Gordon Low]], American founder of the Girl Scouts (d. [[1927]])\n* [[November 1]] &ndash; [[Boies Penrose]], United States Senator from Pennsylvania (d. [[1921]])\n* [[November 2]] &ndash; [[Soapy Smith]], American con artist and gangster (d. [[1898]])\n* [[November 6]] &ndash; [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]], Polish pianist and composer (d. [[1941]])\n* [[November 16]] &ndash; [[John Henry Kirby]], Texas legislator, American businessman (d. [[1940]])\n* [[November 23]] &ndash; [[Hjalmar Branting]], [[Prime Minister of Sweden]], recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1925]])\n* [[December 4]] &ndash; [[Charles de Broqueville]], Belgian Prime Minister (d. [[1940]])\n* [[December 7]] &ndash; [[Joseph Cook]], 6th [[Prime Minister of Australia]] (d. [[1947]])\n* [[December 15]] \n** [[Niels Ryberg Finsen]], Danish physician, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] (d. [[1904]])\n** [[Abner Powell]], American [[Major league baseball]] player (d. [[1953]])\n* [[December 25]] &ndash; [[Manuel Dimech]], Maltese philosopher, social reformer (d. [[1921]])\n* [[December 31]]\n**[[Joseph S. Cullinan]], American oil industrialist, founder of ''[[Texaco]]'' (d. [[1937]])\n**[[John T. Thompson]], United States Army officer, inventor of the [[Thompson gun|Tommy gun]] (d. [[1940]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n\n=== January&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Annabella Byron (1792-1860).jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Lady Byron|Anne Isabella Milbanke]]]]\n* [[January 1]] &ndash; [[Thomas Hobbes Scott]], English clergyman (b. [[1783]])\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; [[John Neumann]], [[Saint]] and [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Philadelphia]] (b. [[1811]])\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Ezequiel Zamora]], leader of the Federalist Army in [[Venezuela]] (b. [[1817]])\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; [[William Mason (U.S. politician)|William Mason]], American politician (b. [[1786]])\n* [[January 18]] &ndash; [[John Nelson (lawyer)]], American lawyer (b. [[1791]])\n* [[January 26]] &ndash; [[Eliza Lee Cabot Follen]], American writer (b. [[1787]])\n* [[January 27]]\n** [[J\u00e1nos Bolyai]], Hungarian mathematician (b. [[1802]])\n** [[Thomas Brisbane]], Scottish astronomer (b. [[1773]])\n* [[January 29]] &ndash;\n** [[Ernst Moritz Arndt]], German writer, poet (b. [[1769]])\n** [[St\u00e9phanie de Beauharnais]], Grand Duchess of Baden (b. [[1789]])\n* [[February 29]] &ndash; [[George Bridgetower]], Afro-Polish violinist (b. [[1778]])\n* [[March 6]] &ndash; [[Justus Johann Friedrich Dotzauer]], German cellist, composer (b. [[1783]])\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Carl Ritter von Ghega]], Albanian-born Venetian road engineer (b. [[1802]])\n* [[March 17]] &ndash; [[Anna Brownell Jameson]], British author (b. [[1794]])\n* [[March 25]] &ndash; [[James Braid (surgeon)|James Braid]], Scottish surgeon (b. [[1795]])\n* [[May 1]] &ndash; [[Anders Sand\u00f8e \u00d8rsted]], 3rd Prime Minister of Denmark (b. [[1778]])\n* [[May 10]] &ndash; [[Theodore Parker]], American preacher, Transcendentalist, and abolitionist (b. [[1810]])\n* [[May 12]] &ndash; Sir [[Charles Barry]], English architect (b. [[1795]])\n* [[May 16]] &ndash; [[Anne Isabella Milbanke]], English wife of [[Lord Byron]] (b. [[1792]])\n* [[May 21]] &ndash; [[Phineas Gage]], improbable American head injury survivor (b. [[1823]])\n* [[June 18]] &ndash; [[Friedrich Wilhelm von Bismarck]], German army officer, writer (b. [[1783]])\n* [[June 30]] &ndash; [[Gotthilf Heinrich von Schubert]], German naturalist (b. [[1780]])\n\n=== July&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Charles Goodyear.png|thumb|110px|right|[[Charles Goodyear]]]]\n[[File:Schopenhauer 1852.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Arthur Schopenhauer]]]]\n* [[July 1]] &ndash; [[Charles Goodyear]], American inventor (b. [[1800]])\n* [[September 12]] &ndash; [[William Walker (filibuster)|William Walker]], American filibuster who was briefly President of [[Nicaragua]] (executed) (b. [[1824]]) \n* [[September 21]] &ndash; [[Arthur Schopenhauer]], German philosopher (b. [[1788]])\n* [[October 12]] &ndash; [[Sir Harry Smith, 1st Baronet|Sir Harry Smith]], English soldier, military commander (b. [[1787]])\n* [[October 22]] &ndash; [[Wanda Malecka]], Polish publisher (b. [[1800]]) \n* [[October 25]] &ndash; [[Alexander Maconochie (penal reformer)|Alexander Maconchie]], Scottish penal reformer (b. [[1787]])\n* [[October 31]] &ndash; [[Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald]], British admiral (b. [[1775]])\n* [[November 1]] &ndash; [[Alexandra Feodorovna (Charlotte of Prussia)]], Empress Consort of Russian Emperor [[Nicholas I of Russia|Nicholas I]] (b. [[1798]])\n* [[December 8]] &ndash; [[Mary Hall Barrett Adams]], American book editor and letter writer (b. [[1816]])\n* [[December 14]] &ndash; [[George Hamilton-Gordon, 4th Earl of Aberdeen]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (b. [[1784]])\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* [[Dai Xi]], Chinese painter (b. [[1801]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1860}}\n[[Category:1860| ]]\n[[Category:Leap years in the Gregorian calendar]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1860|the Italian film|1860 (film)|other uses|Special:Search/intitle:1860}}\n{{Year nav|1860}}\n{{C19 year in topic}}{{Year article header|1860}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n* [[January 2]] &ndash; The discovery of a hypothetical planet [[Vulcan (hypothetical planet)|Vulcan]] is announced at a meeting of the [[French Academy of Sciences]] in Paris, France.\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; The [[Pemberton Mill]] in [[Lawrence, Massachusetts]] collapses, killing 146 workers. \n* [[January 13]] &ndash; [[Battle of T\u00e9touan]], [[Morocco]]: Spanish troops under General Leopoldo O'Donnell, 1st Duke of Tetuan defeat the Moroccan Army.\n* [[January 20]] &ndash; [[Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour]] is recalled as Prime Minister of [[Piedmont-Sardinia]]. \n* [[February 22]] &ndash; Shoe-making workers of [[Lynn, Massachusetts]], strike successfully for higher wages. The strike spreads throughout [[New England]], and eventually involves 20,000 workers. \n* [[February 26]] &ndash; White settlers [[1860 Wiyot massacre|massacre]] a band of [[Wiyot people|Wiyot Indians]] on [[Indian Island (Humboldt Bay)|Indian Island]], near [[Eureka, California]]. At least 60 women, children and elders are killed. [[Bret Harte]], newspaper reporter in [[Arcata]], reports the news to newspapers in [[San Francisco]].\n* [[February 28]] &ndash; The [[Artists Rifles]] is established, as the 38th Middlesex (Artists) Rifle Volunteer Corps, with headquarters at [[Burlington House]] in London.<ref name=Website>See http://www.artistsriflesassociation.org/regiment-artists-rifles.htm.</ref>\n* [[March 6]] &ndash; While campaigning for the [[1860 United States presidential election|presidency]], [[Abraham Lincoln]] makes a speech defending the [[right to strike]]. \n* [[March 9]] &ndash; The first [[Japanese Embassy to the United States (1860)|Japanese ambassadors to the United States]] arrive in [[San Francisco]].\n* [[March 17]] &ndash; The [[First Taranaki War]] begins at [[Waitara, New Zealand]], when [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] refuse to sell land to British settlers. \n* [[March 22]] &ndash; The [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany]] is annexed to the newly formed [[Kingdom of Italy]].\n* [[March 24]] &ndash; [[Sakuradamon Incident (1860)|Sakuradamon Incident]]: [[R\u014dnin]] [[samurai]] of the [[Mito Domain]] in Japan assassinate [[tair\u014d]] (Chief Minister) [[Ii Naosuke]] outside the Sakurada Gate of [[Edo Castle]], disaffected with his role in the opening of Japan to foreign powers.\n* [[March]]&ndash;August &ndash; [[Battle of Jiangnan (1860)|The second rout]] of the [[Jiangnan Daying]] destroys the [[Qing dynasty]]'s army of 180,000.\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; The [[Italian Parliament|first Italian Parliament]] meets at [[Turin]].\n* [[April 3]] &ndash; The [[Pony Express]] begins its first run from [[St. Joseph, Missouri]] to [[Sacramento, California]], with riders carrying [[Pony Express Bible|a small Bible]].\n* [[April 4]] &ndash; A new uprising erupts in [[Palermo]].\n* [[April 9]] &ndash; French typesetter [[\u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville]] sings the French folk song ''[[Au clair de la lune]]'' to his [[phonautograph]], producing the world's earliest known [[sound recording]] (however, it is not rediscovered until [[2008]]).\n* [[May 1]] &ndash; A Chondrite-type [[meteorite]] falls to earth in [[Muskingum County, Ohio|Muskingum County]], [[Ohio]], near the town of [[New Concord, Ohio|New Concord]].\n* [[May 6]] &ndash; [[Expedition of the Thousand]]: [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] and his troops depart from [[Genoa|Quarto]].\n* [[May 8]] &ndash; In [[Granadine Confederation|New Granada]] (modern-day [[Colombia]]) the southern state of [[Cauca Department|Cauca]] secedes from the central government, in protest at the suggestion of increase of presidential powers; [[Magdalena Department|Magdalena]] and [[Bol\u00edvar Department|Bol\u00edvar]] join it; [[Colombian Civil War (1860\u201362)|civil war]] erupts.\n* [[May 9]] &ndash; The U.S. [[Constitutional Union Party (United States)|Constitutional Union Party]] holds its convention, and nominates [[John Bell (Tennessee politician)|John Bell]] for [[President of the United States]].\n* [[May 15]] &ndash; [[Expedition of the Thousand]] &ndash; [[Battle of Calatafimi]]: Troops under [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] defeat the army of [[Naples]] in [[Sicily]].\n* [[May 17]] &ndash; The German association football club ''[[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]]'' is founded.\n* [[May 18]] &ndash; [[Abraham Lincoln]] is selected as the U.S. presidential candidate for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], in Chicago, Illinois.\n* [[May 27]] &ndash; Garibaldi's forces take [[Palermo]], the capital of Sicily.\n* [[May 28]] &ndash; One of the worst storms ever experienced in the region hits the east coast of England, sinking more than 100 ships and killing at least 40 people.<ref>Among those rescued at sea is the crew of the [[brig]] ''Hannah'', captained by George Jezzard, the great-great-great-grandfather of actor [[David Suchet]].</ref>\n* {{OldStyleDate|12 June|1860|31 May}} &ndash; The [[State Bank of the Russian Empire]] is established.\n* [[June 30]] &ndash; A historic [[1860 Oxford evolution debate|debate about evolution]] is held, at the [[Oxford University Museum of Natural History|Oxford University Museum]].\n\n=== July&ndash;September ===\n* [[July 2]] &ndash; [[Vladivostok]] is founded in Russia.\n* [[July 9]] &ndash; The [[Florence Nightingale School of Nursing and Midwifery|Nightingale Training School and Home for Nurses]], the first [[nursing school]] based on the ideas of [[Florence Nightingale]], is opened at [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in London.\n* [[July 11]] &ndash; Mutsuhito (the future [[Emperor Meiji]]) becomes [[Crown Prince]] of Japan.\n* [[July 20]] &ndash; [[Battle of Milazzo (1860)|Battle of Milazzo]]: The forces of [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] defeat royal Neapolitan forces near Messina, bringing nearly all of Sicily under Garibaldi's control.[[File:Giuseppe Garibaldi 1870 Nadar.jpg|thumb|160px|right| [[July 20]]: [[Giuseppe Garibaldi|Garibaldi]].]]\n*[[August 13]] &ndash; [[Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Pav\u00f3n]] (1791-1866) becomes unconstitutional interim [[President of Mexico]], replacing [[Miguel Miram\u00f3n]]. Two days later Miram\u00f3n becomes president again.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Pav\u00f3n|url=https://presidentes.mx/jose-ignacio-pavon|website=Presidentes.mx|language=Spanish|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[August 22]] &ndash; Assisted by the British Navy, the troops of [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] cross from Sicily to the Italian mainland.\n* [[September 1]] A solar [[coronal mass ejection]] hits [[Earth's magnetosphere]], and induces one of the largest geomagnetic storms on record.\n* [[September 3]]&ndash;[[September 5|5]] &ndash; The [[Karlsruhe Congress|First International Chemistry Congress]] is held in [[Karlsruhe]], [[Grand Duchy of Baden|Baden]].\n* [[September 7]]\n** The {{PS|Lady Elgin}} is accidentally rammed and sunk in [[Lake Michigan]]; hundreds drown.\n** [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]]'s forces capture Naples.\n* [[September 10]] &ndash; Piedmontese forces invade the [[Papal States]], hoping to link up with Garibaldi in Naples.\n* [[September 18]] &ndash; [[Battle of Castelfidardo]]: The Piedmontese decisively defeat the Papal forces, allowing them to continue their march into Neapolitan territory, and effectively reducing the [[Papal States]] to the territory around Rome.\n* [[September 24]] &ndash; [[Battle of Guayaquil]]: [[Ecuador]]ian forces, led by [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Flores]] and [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda Moreno]], take the port of Guayaquil from Supreme Chief Guillermo Franco, who is backed by [[Peru]]vian forces.\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n* [[October]] &ndash; [[John Hanning Speke]] and [[James Augustus Grant]] leave [[Zanzibar]], to search for the source of the [[Nile River]].\n* [[October 1]] &ndash; [[Battle of Volturnus (1860)|Battle of Volturnus]]: Garibaldi defeats the last organized army of the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]].\n* [[October 5]] &ndash; Austria, Britain, France, [[Prussia]] and the [[Ottoman Empire]] form a commission to investigate the [[1860 Druze\u2013Maronite conflict|causes of the massacres]] of [[Maronite Christians]], committed by [[Druze]]s in [[Lebanon]] earlier in the year.\n* [[October 17]] &ndash; [[The Open Championship]], also known as the British Open, is played for the first time at [[Prestwick Golf Club]] in [[Ayrshire]], Scotland. The event is won by [[Willie Park Sr]]\n* [[October 18]] &ndash; The first [[Convention of Peking]] formally ends the [[Second Opium War]].\n* [[October 18]]\u2013[[October 21|21]] &ndash; Beijing's [[Old Summer Palace]] is burned to the ground by orders of British general [[James Bruce, 8th Earl of Elgin|Lord Elgin]], in retaliation for mistreatment of several [[prisoners of war]], during the [[Second Opium War]].\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; A new [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] revolt begins in New Zealand.\n* [[October 26]]\n** Garibaldi again defeats the Neapolitan forces, advancing on [[siege of Gaeta (1860)|Gaeta]], the last remaining Neapolitan strong-point.\n** Meeting at [[Teano]]: [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] gives [[Naples]] to King [[Victor Emmanuel II of Italy|Victor Emmanuel II]], recognizing him as [[King of Italy]].\n* [[November 3]] &ndash; The combined forces of [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]] and King [[Victor Emmanuel II of Italy|Victor Emmanuel II]] besiege King [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies]] in [[Gaeta]], his last remaining stronghold.\n* [[November 6]] &ndash; [[1860 United States presidential election|U.S. presidential election]]: [[Abraham Lincoln]] beats [[John C. Breckinridge]], [[Stephen A. Douglas]], and [[John Bell (Tennessee politician)|John Bell]], and is elected as the 16th President of the United States, the first [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to hold that office.\n* [[December 1]] &ndash; [[Charles Dickens]] publishes the first installment of ''[[Great Expectations]]'' in his magazine ''[[All the Year Round]]''.\n* [[December 7]] &ndash; After a fiercely contested campaign, [[Monier Monier-Williams]] [[Boden Professor of Sanskrit election, 1860|is elected]] as the new [[Boden Professor of Sanskrit]], at Oxford University.\n* [[December 20]] &ndash; [[South Carolina]] becomes the first state to secede from the United States.\n[[Image:Hms warrior.jpg|thumb|220px|right| [[December 29]]: {{HMS|Warrior|1860|6}} (restored).]]\n*[[December 24]] &ndash; Mexico's interim president Miguel Miram\u00f3n flees the country after being defeated in battle.<ref name=\"miramon\">{{cite web|title=Miguel Miram\u00f3n|url=https://presidentes.mx/miguel-miramon|website=Presidentes.mx|language=Spanish|accessdate=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[December 26]] &ndash; First [[Rules derby]] is held between [[Sheffield F.C.]] and [[Hallam F.C.]], the oldest football fixture in the world.\n* [[December 29]] &ndash; The world's first ocean-going (all) iron-hulled and armoured [[battleship]], the (British) [[HMS Warrior (1860)|HMS ''Warrior'']], is launched.\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* Christians and [[Druze]]s clash in [[Damascus]], Syria.\n* In [[Buenos Aires]], leader [[Bartolom\u00e9 Mitre]] subverts the [[Argentine Confederation]], and begins to establish a new centralist government, with the help of [[Uruguay]]an [[Colorado Party (Uruguay)|Colorado party]] leader [[Venancio Flores]].\n* China agrees, in an [[unequal treaty]] imposed on it, to allow missionaries to proselytize throughout the country.\n* [[Discovery of the chemical elements]]: [[Robert Bunsen]] discovers [[caesium]] and [[rubidium]].\n* German chemist [[Albert Niemann (chemist)|Albert Niemann]] makes a detailed analysis of the [[coca]] leaf, isolating and purifying the [[alkaloid]], which he calls [[cocaine]].<ref>Niemann, Albert (1860). ''[[On a New Organic Base in the Coca Leaves]]'' (\"\u00dcber eine neue organische Base in den Cocabl\u00e4ttern\", published version of Ph.D. dissertation).</ref> \n* [[Napoleon III]], Emperor of the French, and [[Empress Eug\u00e9nie]] visit [[Algiers]] and stay at the [[Casbah of Algiers]].<ref name=\"WDL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8768/|title=Interior of Governors Palace, Algiers, Algeria|website=[[World Digital Library]]|year=1899|accessdate=2013-09-25}}</ref>\n* [[Augustana College (Illinois)|Augustana College]] is founded in Chicago, Illinois by Scandinavian immigrants.<ref>The college moves to [[Paxton, Illinois]], in [[1862]] and eventually splits into a Swedish college in Rock Island, Illinois, in [[1875]], and a Norwegian college in Sioux Falls, South Dakota, in [[1918]].</ref>\n* Britain produces 20% of the entire world's output of industrial goods.\n* The [[Russian Empire]] has c. {{convert|1250|mi|km}} of railroads.\n* The [[American South]] has c. 4 million slaves.\n* 1860&ndash;[[1900]] &ndash; 14 million immigrants come to the United States.\n* Approximate date &ndash; First recorded [[fish and chip shop]]s in the United Kingdom, Joseph Malin's in London<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2003/jan/19/foodanddrink.restaurants|title=Enduring Love|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|first=Jay|last=Rayner|authorlink=Jay Rayner|date=2003-01-19|accessdate=2019-09-30}}</ref> and John Lees' in [[Mossley]] near [[Oldham]], Lancashire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/10410058/Potted-histories-fish-and-chips.html|title=Potted histories: fish and chips|last=Hyslop|first=Leah|date=2013-10-30|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|accessdate=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n== Births ==\n=== January&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Takaaki Kato suit.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Takaaki Kato]]]]\n[[File:Charles Curtis-portrait.jpg|110px|thumb|[[Charles Curtis]]]]\n\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; [[Kato Takaaki]], 24th [[Prime Minister of Japan]] (d. [[1926]])\n* [[January 8]] &ndash; [[Emma Booth (The Salvation Army)|Emma Booth]], fourth child of [[William Booth|William]] and [[Catherine Booth]] (d. [[1903]])\n* [[January 17]]\n** [[Charles K. French]], American actor, film director, and screenwriter (d. [[1952]])\n** [[Douglas Hyde]], 1st President of Ireland (d. [[1949]])\n* [[January 21]] &ndash; [[Karl Staaff]], Swedish lawyer, politician, 11th Prime Minister of Sweden (d. [[1915]])\n* [[January 25]] &ndash; [[Charles Curtis]], [[List of Vice Presidents of the United States|31st]] [[Vice President of the United States]] (d. [[1936]])\n* [[January 28]] &ndash; [[W. G. Read Mullan]], American Jesuit, academic (d. [[1910]])\n* [[January 29]]\n** [[William Jacob Baer]], American painter (d. [[1941]])\n** [[Anton Chekhov]], Russian writer (d. [[1904]])\n* [[February 11]] &ndash; [[Rachilde]], French author (d. [[1953]])\n* [[February 14]] &ndash; [[Eugen Schiffer]], German politician (d. [[1954]])\n* [[February 18]] &ndash; [[Anders Zorn]], Swedish artist (d. [[1920]]) \n* [[February 25]] &ndash; [[Sir William Ashley]], English economic historian (d. [[1927]])\n* [[February 28]] &ndash; [[Carl Georg Barth]], American [[mathematician]], [[mechanical engineer]] (d. [[1939]])\n* [[February 29]] &ndash; [[Herman Hollerith]], American businessman, inventor (d. [[1929]])\n* [[March 2]] &ndash; [[Susanna M. Salter]], first woman mayor in the United States (d. [[1961]])\n* [[March 5]] &ndash; [[Sam Thompson]], American baseball player (d. [[1922]])\n* [[March 13]] &ndash; [[Hugo Wolf]], Austrian composer (d. [[1903]])\n* [[March 19]] &ndash; [[William Jennings Bryan]], American politician (d. [[1925]])\n* [[March 27]] &ndash; [[Frank Frost Abbott]], American classical scholar (d. [[1924]])\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[Sergey Reformatsky]], Russian chemist (d. [[1934]])\n* [[April 7]] &ndash; [[Will Keith Kellogg]], American industrialist, founder of the [[Kellogg Company]] (d. [[1951]])\n* [[May 2]] &ndash; [[Theodor Herzl]], Austrian founder of modern political Zionism (d. [[1904]])\n* [[May 7]] &ndash; [[Tom Norman]], English freak [[showman]] (d. [[1930]])\n* [[May 9]] &ndash; [[J. M. Barrie]], Scottish author (d. [[1937]])\n* [[May 15]] &ndash; [[Ellen Axson Wilson]], [[First Lady of the United States]] (d. [[1914]])\n* [[May 20]] &ndash; [[Eduard Buchner]], German chemist, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1917]])\n* [[May 21]] &ndash; [[Willem Einthoven]], Dutch inventor, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] (d. [[1927]])\n* [[May 25]] &ndash; [[James McKeen Cattell]], American psychologist (d. [[1944]])\n* [[May 27]] &ndash; [[Manuel Teixeira Gomes]], 7th President of Portugal (d. [[1941]])\n* [[May 29]] &ndash; [[Isaac Alb\u00e9niz]], Spanish composer (d. [[1909]])\n* [[June 13]] &ndash; [[Lancelot Speed]], British illustrator, silent film director (d. [[1931]])\n* [[June 20]] &ndash; [[Jack Worrall]], Australian cricketer, footballer, and coach (d. [[1937]])\n* [[June 22]] &ndash; [[Tom O'Brien (second baseman)|Tom O'Brien]], American 19th century baseball player (d. [[1921]])\n* [[June 23]] &ndash; [[Albert Giraud]], Belgian poet (d. [[1929]])\n* [[June 25]] &ndash; [[Gustave Charpentier]], French composer (d. [[1956]])\n\n=== July&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Lizzie borden.jpg|110px|thumb|right|[[Lizzie Borden]]]]\n[[File:Annie Oakley by Baker's Art Gallery c1880s-crop.jpg|110px|thumb|[[Annie Oakley]]]]\n[[File:Joseph Cook - Crown Studios 03.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Joseph Cook]]]]\n[[File:Georgina Fraser Newhall (1895).png|thumb|110px|[[Georgina Fraser Newhall]]]]\n* [[July 3]] &ndash; [[Charlotte Perkins Gilman]], American feminist (d. [[1935]])\n* [[July 7]] &ndash; [[Gustav Mahler]], Austrian composer (d. [[1911]])\n* [[July 16]] &ndash; [[Otto Jespersen]], Danish linguist, creator of [[Ido (language)|Ido]] and [[Novial]] languages (d.[[1943]])\n* [[July 19]] &ndash; [[Lizzie Borden]], American murder suspect (d. [[1927]])\n* [[July 31]] &ndash; [[Sir George Warrender, 7th Baronet]], British admiral (d. [[1917]])\n* [[August 3]] &ndash; [[William Kennedy Dickson]], Scottish inventor, cinema pioneer, and film director (d. [[1935]])\n* [[August 5]] &ndash; [[Louis Wain]], English artist (d. [[1939]])\n* [[August 7]] &ndash; [[Alan Leo]], British astrologer (d. [[1917]])\n* [[August 8]] &ndash; [[Eliza Putnam Heaton]], American journalist and editor (d. [[1919]])\n* [[August 9]] &ndash; [[Maude Gillette Phillips]], American author and educator (d. unknown)\n* [[August 10]] &ndash; [[Vishnu Narayan Bhatkhande]], Indian musician (d. [[1936]])\n* [[August 13]] &ndash; [[Annie Oakley]], American Wild West show performer (d. [[1926]])\n* [[August 15]]\n**[[Henrietta Vinton Davis]], American elocutionist, dramatist, and impersonator (d. [[1941]])\n**[[Florence Harding]], [[First Lady of the United States]] (d. [[1924]])\n* [[August 16]] &ndash; [[Jules Laforgue]], French poet (d. [[1887]])\n* [[August 20]] &ndash; [[Raymond Poincar\u00e9]], French president (d. [[1934]])\n* [[August 22]] &ndash; [[Alfred Ploetz]], German physician, biologist, and eugenicist (d. [[1940]]) \n* [[August 25]] &ndash; [[George Fawcett]], American actor (d. [[1939]])\n* [[August 26]] &ndash; [[Eudora Stone Bumstead]], American poet and hymnwriter (d. [[1892]])\n* [[September 1]] &ndash; [[Mary E. C. Bancker]], American author (unknown year of death)\n* [[September 2]] &ndash; [[Georgina Fraser Newhall]], Canadian author and the bardess of the Clan Fraser Society of Canada (d. [[1932]])\n* [[September 5]] &ndash; [[Andrew Volstead]], American politician (d. [[1947]])\n* [[September 6]] &ndash; [[Jane Addams]], American social worker, recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1935]])\n* [[September 7]] &ndash; Anna Mary Robertson Moses (aka [[Grandma Moses]]), American painter, centenarian (d. [[1961]])\n* [[September 13]] &ndash; [[John J. Pershing]], American general (d. [[1948]])\n* [[September 15]] &ndash; [[Mokshagundam Visvesvarayya]], Indian engineer, statesman (d. [[1962]])\n* [[October 23]] &ndash; [[Molly Elliot Seawell]], American historian (d. [[1916]])\n* [[October 31]] &ndash; [[Juliette Gordon Low]], American founder of the Girl Scouts (d. [[1927]])\n* [[November 1]] &ndash; [[Boies Penrose]], United States Senator from Pennsylvania (d. [[1921]])\n* [[November 2]] &ndash; [[Soapy Smith]], American con artist and gangster (d. [[1898]])\n* [[November 6]] &ndash; [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]], Polish pianist and composer (d. [[1941]])\n* [[November 16]] &ndash; [[John Henry Kirby]], Texas legislator, American businessman (d. [[1940]])\n* [[November 23]] &ndash; [[Hjalmar Branting]], [[Prime Minister of Sweden]], recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1925]])\n* [[December 4]] &ndash; [[Charles de Broqueville]], Belgian Prime Minister (d. [[1940]])\n* [[December 7]] &ndash; [[Joseph Cook]], 6th [[Prime Minister of Australia]] (d. [[1947]])\n* [[December 15]] \n** [[Niels Ryberg Finsen]], Danish physician, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] (d. [[1904]])\n** [[Abner Powell]], American [[Major league baseball]] player (d. [[1953]])\n* [[December 25]] &ndash; [[Manuel Dimech]], Maltese philosopher, social reformer (d. [[1921]])\n* [[December 31]]\n**[[Joseph S. Cullinan]], American oil industrialist, founder of ''[[Texaco]]'' (d. [[1937]])\n**[[John T. Thompson]], United States Army officer, inventor of the [[Thompson gun|Tommy gun]] (d. [[1940]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n\n=== January&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Annabella Byron (1792-1860).jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Lady Byron|Anne Isabella Milbanke ]]]]\n* [[January 1]] &ndash; [[Thomas Hobbes Scott]], English clergyman (b. [[1783]])\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; [[John Neumann]], [[Saint]] and [[Roman Catholic Bishop of Philadelphia]] (b. [[1811]])\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Ezequiel Zamora]], leader of the Federalist Army in [[Venezuela]] (b. [[1817]])\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; [[William Mason (U.S. politician)|William Mason]], American politician (b. [[1786]])\n* [[January 18]] &ndash; [[John Nelson (lawyer)]], American lawyer (b. [[1791]])\n* [[January 26]] &ndash; [[Eliza Lee Cabot Follen]], American writer (b. [[1787]])\n* [[January 27]]\n** [[J\u00e1nos Bolyai]], Hungarian mathematician (b. [[1802]])\n** [[Thomas Brisbane]], Scottish astronomer (b. [[1773]])\n* [[January 29]] &ndash;\n** [[Ernst Moritz Arndt]], German writer, poet (b. [[1769]])\n** [[St\u00e9phanie de Beauharnais]], Grand Duchess of Baden (b. [[1789]])\n* [[February 29]] &ndash; [[George Bridgetower]], Afro-Polish violinist (b. [[1778]])\n* [[March 6]] &ndash; [[Justus Johann Friedrich Dotzauer]], German cellist, composer (b. [[1783]])\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Carl Ritter von Ghega]], Albani